[Patient] Yo doc, I been feelin' real tired lately. What should I be drinkin' to help with my heart failure?

[Healthcare Specialist] Hey there, I hear you. It's important to watch your fluid intake when you have heart failure. You should aim to drink about 6-8 cups of fluid a day. Water is the best choice.

[Patient] Got it, I'll make sure to drink more water. What about other drinks like juice or soda?

[Healthcare Specialist] It's best to limit drinks with added sugar like juice and soda. They can make your heart failure worse. Stick to water and maybe some low-sugar options like unsweetened tea.

[Patient] Okay, I'll cut back on the sugary drinks. What about coffee and tea?

[Healthcare Specialist] Coffee and tea are okay in moderation, but try not to have too much caffeine. It can make your heart work harder. Stick to one or two cups a day.

[Patient] Cool, I'll keep that in mind. What about alcohol?

[Healthcare Specialist] It's best to limit alcohol when you have heart failure. It can affect your heart and interact with your medications. If you do drink, keep it to a minimum.

[Patient] Got it, I'll be careful with alcohol. What about sports drinks?

[Healthcare Specialist] Sports drinks can be high in sugar and sodium, so it's best to avoid them. Stick to water to stay hydrated.

[Patient] Alright, I'll skip the sports drinks. What about milk and dairy?

[Healthcare Specialist] Milk and dairy are fine in moderation, but try to choose low-fat or fat-free options. They can be high in saturated fat, which isn't good for your heart.

[Patient] I'll stick to low-fat dairy then. What about smoothies?

[Healthcare Specialist] Smoothies can be a good option, just watch out for added sugars. Try making your own with fruits and veggies for a healthy choice.

[Patient] Sounds good, I'll try making my own smoothies. What about soups?

[Healthcare Specialist] Soups can be a good way to stay hydrated, just watch out for high-sodium options. Choose low-sodium broths and add lots of veggies for a heart-healthy choice.

[Patient] I'll look for low-sodium soups then. What about herbal teas?

[Healthcare Specialist] Herbal teas can be a good choice, just make sure they don't have any caffeine. Some herbal teas can be soothing and hydrating.

[Patient] I'll try some herbal teas for a change. Thanks for all the info, doc.

[Healthcare Specialist] No problem, happy to help. Remember, staying hydrated is key for managing your heart failure. Let me know if you have any more questions.